1
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:41,000
Hello. Yes, I'll get her.

2
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:46,000
Yes,
I'll tell her. All right. Bye.

3
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:49,000
I've got a message
for you. A secret one.

4
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:51,000
[ Blows Raspberry ] Aah!

5
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:01,000
When I was but 13 or so,
I went into a golden land.

6
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:05,000
Chimbarozo Cotopaxi
took me by the hand.

7
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:27,000
Over the Orinoco. Across
the blazing Kalahari Desert.

8
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:29,000
Through the untamed
grasslands of the Veldt.

9
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:11,000
What is it? What did she say?

10
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:20,000
What did she say that
for? It's all right. I don't mind.

11
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:23,000
Everything's
going to be all right.

12
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:51,000
<i>** [ Woman Humming ]</i>

13
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:57,000
** [ Humming Continues ]

14
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:53,000
[ Groans ]

15
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:07,000
Hils, wake up.

16
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:11,000
Mummy's made a
new song for us to play.

17
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:50,000
B-flat. Listen.

18
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:05,000
Big waves,
rolling in three-four time.

19
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:10,000
<i>And when you hear me
change to the major chord,</i>

20
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:13,000
<i>I want you to dive
down under the sea.</i>

21
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:18,000
<i>Dive down under the waves.</i>

22
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:21,000
<i>Little silvery fishes swimming
in and out of the seaweed...</i>

23
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:23,000
<i>in six-eight time.</i>

24
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:28,000
And... watch out.
Here comes the shark.

25
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:31,000
[ Pounds Keys, Roaring ]

26
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:35,000
[ Roaring Continues
] [ Girls Laughing ]

27
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:42,000
"Dear Mrs. Du Pre,
we are planning to broadcast...

28
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:45,000
a children's performance of
the <i>Toy Symphony</i> by..." Haydn.

29
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:47,000
Very good.

30
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:51,000
"We would be delighted if you would conduct
and Hilary would play the flute part."

31
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:56,000
It's from the BBC. Jolly good.
Jolly good. Well done, Hullabaloo.

32
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:59,000
Ha! What about me?

33
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:01,000
If you practice hard enough,
maybe next time.

34
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:03,000
I want to come this time.

35
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:06,000
<i>I want to be with Hilary.</i>

36
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:09,000
Well,
couldn't she just come along for the ride?

37
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:13,000
- It's an orchestra, Derek, not a Clapham omnibus.
- [ Blows Raspberry ]

38
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:16,000
Jackie,
that is quite uncalled-for.

39
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:18,000
You're spoiling
Hilary's special day.

40
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:22,000
If Jackie can't come,
I won't go.

41
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:26,000
<i>** [ Classical ]</i>

42
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:50,000
<i>** [ Stops ]</i> Follow the score.
Don't gawp at the soloist.

43
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:02,000
I really can't apologize enough. Oh,
not at all.

44
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:05,000
Worth any amount of
trouble to get young Hilary.

45
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:08,000
She's really very special. Yes,
I realize that.

46
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:12,000
Your sister's a remarkable
girl. You must be very proud.

47
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:15,000
Oh, we all are,
terribly proud. Good-bye.

48
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:23,000
If you want to be with Hilary,
you have to play as well as Hilary.

49
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:26,000
If you want to be together, you've got to
be as good as each other. Understand?

50
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:28,000
Yes.

51
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:31,000
<i>** [ Cello ]</i>

52
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:46,000
Supper's ready.

53
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:55,000
So I think we should leave
some money on the doorstep...

54
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:58,000
for the burglar to take,
so he wouldn't steal anymore.

55
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:01,000
<i>What do you think?</i> Um...

56
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:04,000
Well,
I think that... [ Humming ]

57
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:16,000
<i>[ Woman ] I want you to
do all the sums on the page.</i>

58
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,000
<i>And then I want you
to... [ Dialogue Fades ]</i>

59
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:49,000
<i>[ Woman ] And the first prize
goes to the Du Pre sisters,</i>

60
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:52,000
<i>Jacqueline and
Hilary. Well done.</i>

61
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:56,000
<i>[ Applause ]</i> There's one
for you and one for you.

62
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:05,000
<i>[ Applause Continues ]</i>

63
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:23,000
Shall I take that for you? <i>* La,
la, la, la, la, la, la, la, *</i>

64
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:25,000
* La, la, la, la,
la, la, la, la, *

65
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:27,000
* La, la, la, la,
la, la, la, la *

66
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:29,000
* La, la, la, la, la, la, la *

67
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:32,000
[ Instruments Tuning ]
<i>[ Humming Continues ]</i>

68
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:57,000
<i>[ Woman ] In the
woodwind category,</i>

69
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:00,000
a very clear winner,
with the highest number of points...

70
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:03,000
<i>ever awarded in this
section of this festival.</i>

71
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:05,000
Hilary Du Pre.

72
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:10,000
Well done.

73
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:32,000
We had no difficulty at all in choosing
the winner in the string section,

74
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:35,000
<i>even though we
were a little unnerved...</i>

75
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:39,000
by the candidate's rather
overemphatic bodily movements.

76
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:42,000
<i>I think this must
be the first time...</i>

77
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:46,000
that our winning soloists
have been sisters.

78
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:51,000
<i>The judges were unanimous...</i>

79
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:55,000
in choosing Miss
Jacqueline Du Pre.

80
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:06,000
[ Audience Cheering ]

81
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:38,000
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,
we have plenty more awards,</i>

82
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:41,000
<i>so I'd be grateful if you all could
sit down... [ Dialogue Fades ]</i>

83
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:57,000
<i>[ Cheering, Applause Continue ]</i>

84
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:16,000
She does bob about a bit.

85
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:20,000
She looks like one of
these bobby-soxer types.

86
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:22,000
I'm afraid that's my fault.

87
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:25,000
They did a lot of musical
movement when they were younger.

88
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:28,000
Can we have a picture,
please? You too, sir.

89
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:30,000
That's lovely. Yeah.

90
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:32,000
You give me some
nice big smiles.

91
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:38,000
Hils! Hils!

92
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:40,000
Come over.

93
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:46,000
This is one of yours too? Does
she play? <i>[ Mother ] Oh, yes.</i>

94
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:49,000
Hilary won as well,
didn't you, dear?

95
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:52,000
We can have a family portrait.

96
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:54,000
<i>Hold your flute up. Smile then.</i>

97
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:57,000
Your sister's a remarkable
girl. You must be very proud.

98
00:14:57,000 --> 00:15:00,000
Oh, yes, we are, terribly proud.

99
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:03,000
Smile then.

100
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:19,000
<i>[ Speaking,
[ Speaking, Indistinct ]</i>

101
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:24,000
Well, be good.

102
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:26,000
We'll collect you in an hour.

103
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:29,000
Be good. Yes.

104
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:44,000
Now, let's see what you can do.

105
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:56,000
An hour today and
then see how we go.

106
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:58,000
Oh.

107
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:14,000
Well, now, this is nice.

108
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:31,000
<i>** [ Cello ]</i>

109
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:45,000
No.

110
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:49,000
Try that... that lifting,
that upbeat before the three quavers...

111
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:52,000
with an up bow like... like so.

112
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:02,000
<i>[ Jackie ] I like him.
He's my cello daddy.</i>

113
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:05,000
I want to come every
day. Can I come every day?

114
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:09,000
Do you mind? We
shall have to get a car.

115
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:37,000
[ Flute Hits Window ]

116
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:43,000
<i>[ Door Opens ]</i>

117
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:47,000
<i>[ Door Shuts ]</i>

118
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:21,000
<i>** [ Continues ]</i>

119
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:37,000
That's it.

120
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:39,000
She's ready.

121
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:44,000
<i>Mrs. Du Pre, what do you think of
a debut recital at the Wigmore Hall?</i>

122
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:46,000
Marvelous. <i>I've spoken
to Ibbs and Tillot.</i>

123
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:49,000
They'll handle the
publicity and the tickets.

124
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:52,000
And to Ernest Lush. He'll
accompany her on the piano.

125
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:54,000
Oh.

126
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:24,000
- [ Playing Off-key ]
- She's playing flat.

127
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:27,000
** [ Stops ]

128
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:31,000
Ladies and gentlemen, I'm afraid
that my "A" string has come loose,

129
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:34,000
and I'm going to have to
re-string my cello and start again.

130
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:37,000
<i>[ Audience Murmuring ]</i>

131
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:42,000
Well, at least it wasn't
my G-string. <i>** [ Cello ]</i>

132
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:10,000
<i>[ Applause, Cheering ]</i>

133
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:22,000
I do wish she'd
keep that head still.

134
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:25,000
It looks so flamboyant,
all that hair flying about the place.

135
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:29,000
[ Chattering,
Laughter ] There she is.

136
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:32,000
Oh. <i>That was wonderful.</i>

137
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:35,000
They want me to play at a wedding,
in Italy.

138
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:38,000
It's a princess's wedding.

139
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:41,000
You will come? I'd be
terrified on my own. Oh, Jack...

140
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:43,000
Congratulations. You
were wonderful. Thank you.

141
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:48,000
<i>Um, excuse me, everyone. Attention,
please. Thank you.</i>

142
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:50,000
Jackie's debut went very well.

143
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:52,000
Um, I'm sure you would agree.

144
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:56,000
And to mark the occasion,
a very generous friend,

145
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:58,000
who wishes to remain anonymous,

146
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:01,000
has offered her this.

147
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:12,000
It's one of the finest
cellos ever made.

148
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:17,000
It's called The Davidov.

149
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:26,000
The magic is in the varnish.

150
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:29,000
So you must keep it away
from extremes of temperature.

151
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:32,000
<i>Another problem
is the insurance.</i>

152
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:35,000
<i>So don't let it get
out of your sight.</i>

153
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:38,000
It will give you the world,
Jackie,

154
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:41,000
but you must give it yourself.

155
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:57,000
[ Speaking Mock Italian ]

156
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:15,000
[ Mock Italian Continues ]

157
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:22,000
<i>Bellissimo! Si, bellissimo!</i>

158
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:24,000
<i>Bellissimo! Si, fortissimo!</i>

159
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:28,000
[ Laughing ] Shh, shh.

160
00:22:55,000 --> 00:22:57,000
[ Glasses Clink ]

161
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:04,000
[ Champagne Bubbling ]

162
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:09,000
[ Whispering ] This is
so loud. [ Both Laughing ]

163
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:13,000
Okay. Here's to Hilary and
Jackie and all who sail in her.

164
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:15,000
[ Snickers ]

165
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:20,000
Mm.

166
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:22,000
Look, Hils.

167
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:31,000
<i>[ Hilary ] We're in Heaven.</i>

168
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:34,000
<i>[ Woman ] Oh,
put that bloody light out.</i>

169
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:47,000
<i>[ Bell Tolling ]</i>

170
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:54,000
Excuse me. Have
you seen my sister?

171
00:23:54,000 --> 00:23:57,000
Is your sister Jacqueline Du Pre? Yes,
that's right.

172
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:02,000
She'll be in Berlin by now. She's
playing <i>The Haydn Cello Concerto in C.</i>

173
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:04,000
Oh.

174
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:10,000
Are you going back to London? Yes,
I suppose so.

175
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:14,000
<i>[ Tolling Continues ]</i>

176
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:17,000
<i>[ Thunder Rumbles ]</i>

177
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:42,000
<i>** [ Flute ]</i>

178
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:52,000
Stop, stop, stop, stop, stop.

179
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:56,000
What is this blasted
jigging about?

180
00:24:56,000 --> 00:25:00,000
Stand still, girl. Stand still.

181
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:05,000
It is impossible to produce a proper
tone without proper deportment.

182
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:20,000
[ Sighs ] You have no technique.

183
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:23,000
That's all right.
Technique can be taught.

184
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:27,000
<i>We just have to go back to
the beginning and start again.</i>

185
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:32,000
- Cancel any concert dates you may have outstanding.
- Yes, Mr. Bentley.

186
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:46,000
Oh, Hilary,
how's your marvelous sister?

187
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:49,000
I'm not sure. She's away
at the moment. In Russia.

188
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:51,000
Oh.

189
00:25:57,000 --> 00:26:01,000
[ Stations Tuning ]

190
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:08,000
** [ Flute ] That's it, old boy.

191
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:11,000
Keep trying. [ Static ]

192
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:14,000
[ Man Speaking
Russian ] That's it!

193
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:17,000
[ Speaking Continues ]

194
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:19,000
Ooh! Felt that.

195
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:22,000
Oh! Now, listen. Well done, boy.

196
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:25,000
<i>What is it?</i> That
is Radio Moscow.

197
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:32,000
This is what Jackie will be hearing
if she's listening to the wireless.

198
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:35,000
[ All Chuckling ]

199
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:41,000
No.

200
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:47,000
No. No! No! No!

201
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:55,000
Instead of
rehearsing this piece,

202
00:26:55,000 --> 00:26:57,000
I just want you to
practice playing B-flat.

203
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:02,000
Just the note B-flat? <i>The note.</i>

204
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:04,000
<i>Just the note.</i>

205
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:17,000
Parcel from Jacks, everybody!

206
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:22,000
Help? Come on. Open it.

207
00:27:22,000 --> 00:27:27,000
Can't open it. Here. Here,
here, here. Let me.

208
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:33,000
<i>[ Mother ] It's her washing.</i>

209
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:38,000
I suppose it must be difficult getting
her washing done in a foreign country.

210
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:47,000
Good afternoon, Madam.

211
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:50,000
My niece is a student... [ Continues,
Indistinct ]

212
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:01,000
Ah, Miss Du Pre. Yes?

213
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:04,000
I was wondering whether I
could book you for a concert.

214
00:28:04,000 --> 00:28:07,000
- It's not me you want. It's my sister.
- But you're Hilary Du Pre.

215
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:10,000
The flautist. Well,
it's you I want. Yes.

216
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:14,000
<i>The Bach,
B Minor.</i> Oh. Oh, I'm sorry.

217
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:16,000
I'm not allowed to play
concerts until after my exam.

218
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:20,000
- Well, when's your exam?
- Now, as a matter of fact.

219
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:22,000
Well, in that case, I'll wait.

220
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:30,000
Please.

221
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:32,000
Good.

222
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:34,000
Good.

223
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:36,000
Good.

224
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:45,000
Would you like to try that for us again,
please, Hilary?

225
00:28:54,000 --> 00:28:56,000
Again.

226
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:05,000
<i>Again!</i>

227
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:19,000
Uh, Miss Du Pre?

228
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:40,000
<i>** [ Cello ]</i>

229
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:22,000
Oh, do I get my booking?

230
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:26,000
Oh, I'm terribly sorry.

231
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:29,000
Well,
you ran off. I followed you home.

232
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:33,000
You don't mind, do you?

233
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:37,000
No,

234
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:40,000
as a matter of fact.

235
00:30:43,000 --> 00:30:47,000
I'd ask you in, but, um,

236
00:30:47,000 --> 00:30:49,000
it's a bit awkward.

237
00:30:49,000 --> 00:30:51,000
My sister's just come home.

238
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:02,000
Well...

239
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:06,000
